ish Jose, Mauricio, Abelardo, Florencio, Francisco, Jorge, Luis, Manuel, Pedro, Soledad, Vicente.  Eastern Slavic Dmytro, Liya, Pyotr, Sergey.","Catalan: habitational name from a place so named in the district of La Garrotxa, Catalonia.","Basque: topographic name for someone who lived by a wood, from <i>baso</i> ‘wood, forest’."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Basset was born about 1160, in Wallingford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thurston Basset. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ralph Gernon II. She died in 1244, at the age of 85."},"et":{"Abt 1160–1244":"umbes 1160–1244","1160–1244":"1160–1244","1152–1247":"1152–1247","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1190–1258":"1190–1258","1097–1175":"1097–1175","1190":"1190","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1244":"1244","1175":"1175","abt 1185":"umbes 1185","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","1160":"1160","Stansted, Essex, Eng.":"Stansted Mountfitchet, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stansted Village, Essex, England":"Stansted Village, Essex, England","Wallingford, Berkshire, England":"Wallingford, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, England":"Thurleigh, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1160–1244":"noin 1160–1244","1160–1244":"1160–1244","1152–1247":"1152–1247","1185–Fema